ound:Plum;\"| || style=\"background:Yellow;\"|WINNER\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Luis || style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || style=\"background:CornflowerBlue;\"| || style=\"background:LemonChiffon;\"|SB || style=\"background:CornflowerBlue;\"| || style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || style=\"background:CornflowerBlue;\"| || style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:CornflowerBlue;\"| || style=\"background:LimeGreen;\"|Runner-up\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Richard || style=\"background:CornflowerBlue;\"| || style=\"background:LemonChiffon;\"|SB  || style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || style=\"background:LemonChiffon;\"|SB || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:plum;\"| || colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:LemonChiffon;\"|SB || style=\"background:LimeGreen;\"|Runner-up\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Chetna || colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || style=\"background:LemonChiffon;\"|SB || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || style=\"background:OrangeRed;\"|OUT || style=\"background:Silver;\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Martha || style=\"background:CornFlowerBlue;\"| || colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:lightblue;\"|  ||style=\"background:plum;\"| || style=\"background:lightblue;\" | || style=\"background:Plum;\"| || style=\"background:OrangeRed;\"|OUT || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:Silver;\" |\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Kate || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:CornflowerBlue;\"| || style=\"background:LemonChiffon;\"|SB || style=\"background:plum;\"| || style=\"background:OrangeRed;\"|OUT || colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:Silver;\" | \n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Norman || style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:plum;\"| || style=\"background:OrangeRed;\"|OUT || colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:Silver;\"|\n|-\n| align=\"left\"|Diana || colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || style=\"background:Chocolate;\"|WD || colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:Silver;\" |\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Iain || style=\"background:Plum;\"| || colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || style=\"background:OrangeRed;\"|OUT || colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:Silver;\"|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Jordan || style=\"background:Plum;\"| || style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || style=\"background:OrangeRed;\"|OUT || colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:Silver;\"|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Enwezor || style=\"background:lightblue;\"| || style=\"background:OrangeRed;\"|OUT || colspan=\"8\" style=\"background:Silver;\"|\n|-\n|align=\"left\"| Claire || style=\"background:OrangeRed;\"|OUT || colspan=\"9\" style=\"background:Silver;\"|\n|}\n<small>{{note|1|[a]}}Diana left the show after episode 4 due to illness. Her departure was announced at the start of episode 5. The night before episode 5 was scheduled to be taped, she suffered a head injury, resulting in an overnight stay in [[Emergency department|A&E]] and a loss of her senses of taste and smell that persisted.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28964737 |title=Great British Bake Off: Diana Beard's exit announced |work=BBC |date=28 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-09-12/great-british-bake-offs-diana-beard-says-her-conscience-is-clear-following-bingate-row |title=Great British Bake Off's Diana Beard says her \"conscience is clear\" following 'bingate' row |work=RadioTimes |date=12 September 2014}}</ref></small>\n\n<small>{{note|2|[b]}}Because the judges were unable to agree, no-one was eliminated this week.</small>\n\n'''Colour key:'''\n\n:{{Color box|Plum|border=darkgray}} Baker was one of the judges' least favourite bakers that week, but was not eliminated.\n:{{Color box|CornflowerBlue|border=darkgray}} Baker was one of the judges' favourite bakers that week, but was not the Star Baker.\n:{{Color box|Lightblue|border=darkgray}} Baker got through to the next round.\n:{{Color box|OrangeRed|border=darkgray}} Baker was eliminated.\n:{{Color box|Chocolate|border=darkgray}} Baker withdrew from the show.\n:{{Color box|LemonChiffon|border=darkgray}} Baker was the Star Baker.\n:{{Color box|LimeGreen|border=darkgray}} Baker was the series runner-up.\n:{{Color box|Yellow|border=darkgray}} Baker was the series winner.\n\n== Episodes ==\n:{{Color box|pink|border=darkgray}} Baker eliminated \n:{{Color box|#d0f0c0|border=darkgray}} Star Baker\n:{{Color box|gold|border=darkgray}} Winner\n\n=== Episode 1: Cakes ===\nFor their first bake, the contestants were required to make a [[Swiss roll|Swiss Roll]] as their signature challenge in two and a half hours. For the technical bake, the baker were set the challenge of baking a [[cherry cake]] in two hours using Mary Berry's recipe. In the showstopper challenge, the bakers were given three and a half hours to bake their own choice of classic British cakes in miniature. The bakers needed to make 36 cakes of identical size, shape and texture.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Baker\n! Signature<br><small>([[Swiss Roll]])</small>\n! Technical<br><small>([[cherry cake|Cherry Cake]])</small>\n! Showstopper<br><small>(36 Classic Miniature British Cakes)</small>\n|-\n| Chetna || Cardamom, Pistachio and Coffee Swiss Roll ||align=\"center\"| 3rd || Tiered [[Victoria Sponge]]s with Lemon Curd and Raspberry Cream\n|- style=\"background:pink;\"\n| Claire || Chocolatey Orangey Swirly Roll || align=\"center\"|8th || Mini Chocolate and Cherry Cakes\n|-\n| Diana || Mum's Sunday Tea Lemon Curd Swiss Roll || align=\"center\"|5th || Chocolate [[Ganache]] Surprises\n|-\n| Enwezor || Raspberry and Lemon Swiss Roll || align=\"center\"|9th || Coffee and Walnut [[Battenberg Cake|Battenberg]] Squares\n|-\n| Iain || Apricot and Basil Swiss Roll with [[Mascarpone]] and White Chocolate Cream || align=\"center\"|4th || Lemon Drizzle Cakes with [[Mascarpone]] Filling, Drizzled Icing, and Candied Lemon\n|-\n| Jordan || [[Kawaii]] Frasier Swiss Roll || align=\"center\"|12th || Lemon Drizzle Cakes with Blueberry and Lemon Curd\n|-\n| Kate || Red Velvet and White Chocolate Swiss Roll || align=\"center\"|6th || Mini Tiered Victoria Sponges\n|-\n| Luis || Spanish Swiss Roll ||align=\"center\"| 7th || Raspberry and Lemon [[Genoise]] Slices with Lemon Drizzles\n|-\n| Martha || [[Tiramisu]] Swiss Roll || align=\"center\"|2nd || Mini Lemon and Thyme Drizzle Cakes\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| Nancy || Coffee and Hazelnut Swiss Roll || align=\"center\"|1st || [[Jaffa Cakes|Jaffa]] Orange Cakes\n|-\n| Norman || [[Black Forest Cake|Black Forest]] Swiss Roll || align=\"center\"|11th || Almond and Raspberry Mini Cakes\n|-\n| Richard || Pistachio and Strawberry Swiss Roll || align=\"center\"|10th || Miniature Coffee and Walnut Cakes\n|}\n\n=== Episode 2: Biscuits ===\nIn this episode, the bakers were challenged with creating biscuits. Firstly, in the signature, they had two hours to bake 36 savoury biscuits. In the technical challenge, they had one and a quarter hours with Mary Berry's recipe for 18 [[florentine biscuit|florentines]], which the bakers found difficult. In the final challenge, the bakers had four hours to make some kind of 3D biscuit scene.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Baker\n! Signature<br><small>(36 Savoury Biscuits)</small>\n! Technical<br><small>(18 [[Florentine biscuit|Florentines]])</small>\n! Showstopper<br><small>(3D Biscuit Scene)</small>\n|-\n| Chetna || [[Fenugreek]] and [[Ajwain|Carom]] Crackers || align=\"center\"|8th || Day On The Beach\n|-\n| Diana || Parmesan Triangles || align=\"center\" |7th || Express, First Class\n|- style=\"background:pink;\"\n| Enwezor || Pumpkin and Sunflower Savoury Biscuits || align=\"center\"|9th || Space Adventure Moon Scene\n|-\n| Iain || [[Za'atar]] and Fig Biscuits || align=\"center\"|11th || Wild West Scene\n|-\n| Jordan || [[Sourdough]], Parmesan and Chilli Biscuits || align=\"center\"|6th || Monster Attack\n|-\n| Kate || Parmesan and Apple Biscuits ||align=\"center\"| 4th || Tea Time\n|-\n| Luis || [[Black olive|Black Olive]] and Rosemary Biscuits with Caramelised Onion Glaze || align=\"center\"|3rd || George Versus The Dragon\n|-\n| Martha || Caramelised Onion and Goat's Cheese Sandwich Biscuits || align=\"center\"|5th || Ski Village Scene\n|-\n| Nancy || Fennel and Rye Thins || align=\"center\"|2nd || Hansel and Gretel Scene\n|-\n| Norman || [[Farthing (British coin)|Farthing]] Biscuits || align=\"center\"|10th || Zulu Boats at Dawn\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| Richard || Rosemary Seeded Crackers || align=\"center\"|1st || Pirates!\n|}\n\n=== Episode 3: Bread ===\nIn bread week, the bakers firstly had to make twelve [[rye bread]] [[Bread roll|rolls]] in three and a half hours. In the technical challenge, they were given three hours to make four [[ciabatta]] loaves using Paul's recipe, with the advice from Paul that they should be patient. In the showstopper, the bakers were required to make a bread centrepiece in four hours. The centrepiece should be a filled-loaf that is spectacular and tasty, and would be judged on its appearance, design and crust, and should be well-baked on the inside.<small><nowiki/></small>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n!Baker\n!Signature\n(12 [[Rye bread|Rye Bread]] [[Bread roll|Rolls]])\n!Technical\n(4 [[Ciabatta]]s)\n!Showstopper\n(Filled Centrepiece Loaf)\n|-\n| Chetna || Onion and [[Pine Nut]] Rolls || align=\"center\" |8th || Rolled and Filled Twin Loaf \n|-\n| Diana || Rustic Picnic Rolls || align=\"center\" |7th || Sharing Savoury Pinwheel\n|-\n| Iain || Cranberry and Walnut Rye Bread Rolls || align=\"center\" |9th || Moroccan Plaited with a [[Bessara]] Dip\n|- style=\"background:pink;\"\n| Jordan || Rye and [[Spelt]] Bread Rolls || align=\"center\" |10th || Strawberry Raspberry [[Cheesecake]] [[Brioche]]\n|-\n| Kate || Orange and [[Cardamom]] Rye Bread Knots || align=\"center\" |1st || [[Prosciutto]], Olive & [[Coriander]] Bread\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| Luis || Opposites Attract Rolls || align=\"center\" |2nd || [[Rosc\u00f3n de Reyes]]\n|-\n| Martha || Date and Walnut Rye Rolls || align=\"center\" |3rd || Stuffed Sunflower Loaf\n|-\n| Nancy || Cider and Walnut Crusty Rolls || align=\"center\" |5th || '[[Full English]]' [[Stromboli (food)|Stromboli]]\n|-\n| Norman || Rye Bread Rolls || align=\"center\" |4th || Chicken and Roasted Vegetable Picnic Loaf\n|-\n| Richard || Rye and Cranberry Rolls || align=\"center\" |6th || [[Pesto]] Pinwheel\n|}\n\n=== Episode 4: Desserts ===\nFor the signature bake, the judges gave the bakers two hours to make eight self-saucing puddings, meaning the sauce should come from the bake itself. The bakers may choose to make either a [[Molten chocolate cake|fondant]] or a sponge which creates its own sauce at the bottom. In the technical, they had to bake Mary's own [[tiramisu]] cake recipe in two and a half hours. In the showstopper, they had four and a half hours to make [[baked Alaska]]s.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Baker\n! Signature<br><small>(8 Self-Saucing Puddings)</small>\n! Technical<br><small>(Tiramisu Cake)</small>\n! Showstopper<br><small>([[Baked Alaska]])</small>\n|-\n| Chetna || Rhubarb, Strawberry and Orange Puddings ||  align=\"center\"|3rd || Mango, Raspberry and Coconut Baked Alaska\n|- \n| Diana || [[Fruit curd|Orange and Lemon Curd]] Pots ||align=\"center\"| 9th || Raspberry Ripple Alaska Swan\n|- style=\"background:pink;\"\n| Iain || Chocolate, Lime and Raspberry Fondants || align=\"center\"|6th || Chocolate, Black Sesame Seed and Coffee Caramel Baked Alaska (not presented)\n|-\n| Kate || Chocolate and Salted Caramel Molten Puddings || align=\"center\"|7th || Pistachio, Raspberry and Chocolate Baked Alaska\n|-\n| Luis || Pears in Puddings || align=\"center\"|2nd || [[Bakewell tart|Bakewell]] Alaska\n|-\n| Martha || Peanut Butter Chocolate Fondants || align=\"center\"|1st || [[Key Lime Pie|Key Lime]] Baked Alaska\n|-\n| Nancy || Pistachio Puddings with Chocolate Sauce ||align=\"center\"| 4th || [[Summer pudding|Summer Pudding]] Alaska\n|-\n| Norman || Mini [[Sticky toffee pudding|Sticky Toffee Pudding]]s || align=\"center\"|8th || Baked Alaska with Strawberry Surprise \n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| Richard || Black Forest Chocolate Fondants || align=\"center\"|5th || Tiramisu Baked Alaska\n|}\nMany of the bakers struggled to make baked Alaskas, as it was the hottest day of the year so far, and two of five refrigerators were broken, resulting in a struggle among the contestants for enough freezer space.<ref name=\"guardian-ian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/aug/28/great-british-bake-off-ian-watters-speaks-diana-beard|title=Great British Bake Off: Iain Watters speaks out as Diana Beard quits|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=August 28, 2014|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref> During the bake, Diana took Iain's ice cream and sponge cake assembly out of the freezer to make room for hers, mistakenly leaving it out on a counter in the hot tent. When Iain found it, the ice cream had melted and, frustrated, he threw the sponge cake and melted ice cream in the dustbin. (It was later stated by producers that the dessert was only out for one minute.) Paul and Mary chastised him for this decision, explaining that they would rather have judged sample pieces of each baked Alaska component or even a melted final product than nothing at all, and his decision to present Paul and Mary with nothing to judge contributed to his elimination. Viewers of the show objected on Twitter, attacking Diana.<ref name=\"guardian-ian\" /> Iain spoke out against these online attacks,<ref name=\"guardian-ian\" /> and Diana claimed that the editing had distorted the truth, \"stitching [her] up\". She subsequently withdrew from the show after suffering an injury from a fall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2736048/Bake-Off-meltdown-Cook-storms-crying-foul-TV-rival-sabotages-ice-cream-pudding.html|title=Great British Bake Off grandmother QUITS show in tears claiming BBC 'stitched her up' over binned pudding scandal, as hundreds complain|date=August 27, 2014|publisher=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Episode 5: Pies and Tarts ===\nFor signature challenge, the bakers were set the task of a family-sized [[custard tart]] in two and a half hours. The tart should have a crispy base and silky custard. The technical challenge is set using one of Paul's recipes, and the bakers were required to make six mini pear pies, which are poached pears surrounded by rough [[puff pastry]], to be completed in two hours. In the showstopper, the bakers were tasked with making tiered pies in four and half hours. The pies needed to be able to support themselves, and should have at least three tiers and share a common theme.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Baker\n! Signature<br/><small>([[custard tart|Custard Tart]])</small>\n! Technical<br/><small>(Mini Pear Pies)</small>\n! Showstopper<br/><small>(Three-Tiered Pie)</small>\n|-\n| Chetna || Rice Custard Tart with Mangoes and Raspberries  || align=\"center\"|2nd || Fusion Tiered Pies\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| Kate || Rhubarb and Custard Tart || align=\"center\"|3rd  || Rhubarb, Prune and Apple Pies \n|-\n| Luis || Tropical [[Manchester tart|Manchester Tart]] || align=\"center\"|6th  || Four Fruity Seasons Tower\n|-\n| Martha || Pistachio, Apricot and Honey Custard Tart || align=\"center\"|1st  || [[Three Little Pigs]] Pie\n|-\n| Nancy || Chocolate Crusted Passion Fruit Tart || align=\"center\" |4th  || Trio of Apple Pies\n|- style=\"background:pink\"\n| Norman || [[Tarte au Citron]] ||align=\"center\"| 5th  || Pieful Tower\n|-\n| Richard || Fig and Orange Tart || align=\"center\"|7th  || Three Course Autumn Pie Feast\n|}\nBefore the round began, it was announced that Diana had withdrawn from the competition for health reasons &ndash; she had lost her sense of taste and smell in a fall.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/aug/28/diana-beard-quit-bake-off-smell-taste|title=Diana Beard: I quit Bake Off after losing sense of taste and smell|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=28 August 2014|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n=== Episode 6: European Cakes ===\nFor the signature bake, the challenge was to bake a cake inspired by a European cake, but the cake must be [[leavened]] with yeast. The bakers were given three hours for the challenge. The technical challenge was set using one of Mary's recipes for a Swedish [[Princess cake]] (''Prinsesst\u00e5rta''). The recipe is the most complicated yet, requiring 26 separate ingredients with 14 stages, and to be completed in two and a quarter hours. For the showstopper challenge, the bakers were required to make a contemporary version of the Hungarian [[Dobos torte|Dobos Torte]] in five hours. The cake should have at least two tiers, with particular emphasis on caramel sugar work on the cake.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Baker\n! Signature<br><small>(Yeast-Leavened Cake)</small>\n! Technical<br><small>([[Princess cake|Prinsesst\u00e5rta]])</small>\n! Showstopper<br><small>([[Dobos Torte]])</small>\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| Chetna || Orange [[Savarin cake|Savarin]] with Cinnamon Cream || align=\"center\"|2nd || Almond Liqueur Dobos Torte with Chocolate Caramel [[Buttercream]]\n|-\n| Kate || Pecan, Chocolate and Sour Cherry [[Babka (cake)|Yeast Cake]] || align=\"center\"|6th || Trio of Dobos Tortes\n|-\n| Luis || Apple and Cinnamon [[Gugelhupf|Kugelhopf]] with Honeyed Apples || align=\"center\" |3rd || The Cage on the Rocky Hill\n|-\n| Martha || Dark Chocolate and Almond Liqueur Savarin || align=\"center\"|4th || Chess-Themed Chocolate and Salted Caramel Dobos Torte\n|-\n| Nancy || Rum Punch Savarin with Coconut Cream and Tropical Fruits || align=\"center\"|1st || Chocolate and Caramel Dobos Torte\n|-\n| Richard || Fruity [[Gugelhupf|Guglhupf]] with an Orange Glaze  || align=\"center\"|5th || Sugar Forest Dobos Torte\n|}\nNo one was eliminated this week as the judges could not agree on the worst-performing baker, stating it was between Richard and Kate. As Diana left the show before the previous week's contest due to illness, it was possible not to eliminate anyone.\n\n=== Episode 7: Pastry ===\n\nIn their first task, the bakers were set the challenge of making twelve savoury pastry parcels, to be completed in an hour and three quarters. The parcels can be of any type of pastries, but should be uniform in size, well-filled, perfectly cooked and well-sealed to prevent leaks. The technical bake was one that for the first time none of the bakers had heard of, the [[Breton people|Breton]] pastry [[kouign-amann]], using one of Paul's recipes. The bakers should make twelve identical kouign-amanns in three and a half hours. For the final challenge, the bakers were required to make 24 [[\u00c9clair]]s of two different flavours (12 of each) in four hours. The \u00e9clairs should be made of [[choux pastry]] and \u00e9clair-shaped, otherwise the bakers were free to do as they wished to produce a showstopper.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Baker\n! Signature<br/><small>(12 Savoury Parcels)</small>\n! Technical<br/><small>([[Kouign-amann|Kouign-Amann]])</small>\n! Showstopper<br/><small>(24 [[\u00c9clair]]s)</small>\n|-\n| Chetna || Crispy Lentil [[Kachori]] || align=\"center\"|6th || Chocolate & Mango and Lemon [[Meringue]] \u00c9clairs\n|- style=\"background:pink\"\n| Kate || Spinach and [[Paneer]] Spicy [[Samosa]] || align=\"center\"|4th || [[Neapolitan ice cream|Neapolitan]] and Lemon Meringue \u00c9clairs\n|-\n| Luis || Childhood [[Empanadas]] || align=\"center\"|5th || Stars and Stripes \u00c9clairs\n|-\n| Martha || Mini [[Beef Wellington]]s || align=\"center\"|3rd || Rhubarb & Custard and Maple Syrup & Bacon \u00c9clairs\n|-\n| Nancy || Spicy Duck [[Pasty|Pasties]] || align=\"center\"|2nd || Smoked Salmon & Horseradish and [[Raspberry Ripple]] \u00c9clairs\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| Richard || Minted Lamb Pasties || align=\"center\"|1st || Stair of \u00c9clairs: Blueberry & Lavender and Raspberry & Rose\n|}\n\n=== Episode 8: Advanced Dough ===\nFor the signature bake, they were given the challenge of making sweet fruit loaves that must be free form. They had two and a half hours for the bake which is challenging as the bakers were required to use enriched dough which takes longer to [[Proofing (baking technique)|proof]]. In the technical, they had two and a half hours to make a [[povitica]], which Chetna had made for her signature loaf. This technical challenge was particularly hard for most of the bakers, many of whose loafs were raw inside and deemed unsafe to eat. [[Doughnuts]] were set as the challenge in the final task, and the bakers were required to make eighteen each of two different sorts, to be completed in four hours.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Baker\n! Signature<br><small>(Fruit Loaf)</small>\n! Technical<br><small>([[Povitica]])</small>\n! Showstopper<br><small>(36 [[Doughnuts]])</small>\n|-\n| Chetna || Date and Walnut Swirl Bread || align=\"center\"|1st || Chocolate Mousse Filled Doughnuts<br>Braided Doughnuts\n|-\n| Luis || Black Forest Cherry Tree || align=\"center\"|2nd || Cocktail Doughnuts\n|- style=\"background:pink\"\n| Martha || Spiced Plum Iced Bread Swirl || align=\"center\"|5th || Glazed Lemon & Poppyseed Doughnuts<br>Chocolate & Passion Fruit Doughnuts\n|-\n| Nancy || [[Lincolnshire]] Plum Braid || align=\"center\"|3rd || Doughnut Family Tree\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| Richard || Fruit Swedish Tea Ring || align=\"center\"|4th || Rhubarb and Custard<br>Toffee Apple Doughnuts\n|}\n\n=== Episode 9: P\u00e2tisserie (Semi-final) ===\nFor the signature challenge, the bakers had to make [[baklava]], including their own [[Filo|filo pastry]], with a time limit of three and a half hours to complete the challenge. There had to be two different types of baklava, and twenty-four portions in total. For the technical challenge, the bakers had to make a [[Baumkuchen#Schichttorte|schichttorte]], and had two hours to complete it. There had to be twenty layers in their schichttorte, and was one of Paul's recipes. For the showstopper challenge, the bakers had to make [[entremets]], very small and fine cakes put in a window of a French [[p\u00e2tisserie]]. They had to make two different types of entremets, twelve of each, and had five hours to complete the challenge. \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Baker \n! Signature<br><small>(24 [[Baklava]])</small>\n! Technical<br><small>([[Baumkuchen#Schichttorte|Schichttorte]])</small>\n! Showstopper<br><small>(24 [[Entremets]])</small>\n|- style=\"background:pink\"\n| Chetna || Chocolate Orange Baklava <br>[[Masala Chai]] Baklava || align=\"center\" |4th || Chocolate, Orange & Nut Entremets<br>Cappuccino Entremets\n|-\n| Luis || Indian Rose Baklava<br>[[Halwa]] Baklava Rolls || align=\"center\"|1st || [[Chocolate Mousse]] & Cherry Entremets<br>Pomegranate, Fig & Pistachio Sponges\n|-\n| Nancy || Coffee and Chocolate Baklava<br>Breakfast Baklava || align=\"center\"|3rd || Raspberry [[Nonnette (dessert)|Nonnettes]]<br>Lime and Passion Fruit Entremets\n|- style=\"background:#d0f0c0\"\n| Richard || Rose and Pistachio Baklava<br>Walnut and Almond Baklava || align=\"center\"|2nd || Hazelnut Mocha Entremets<br>Pink Grapefruit Entremets\n|}\n\n=== Episode 10: Final ===\nIn the final signature challenge, the bakers had to make [[Viennoiserie]] in three and a half hours. They had to make two different types of the pastry. In the technical, the judges decided to bring things \"back to basics\" by asking the bakers to bake 12 [[Victoria Sandwich]]es, [[Tarte au Citron|Tartes au citron]] and [[Scone]]s. The challenge, however, was that they had only two hours to make this and only three instructions. The final Showstopper was a [[Pi\u00e8ce mont\u00e9e|Pi\u00e8ce Mont\u00e9e]]. The bakers were given five hours to make this, and the judges said it must be in some self-standing structure. \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Baker\n! Signature<br><small>([[Viennoiserie]])</small>\n! Technical<br><small>(12 Mini [[Victoria Sandwich]]es, 12 Mini [[Tarte au Citron]], 12 Mini [[Scones]])</small>\n! Showstopper<br><small>([[Pi\u00e8ce mont\u00e9e|Pi\u00e8ce Mont\u00e9e]])</small>\n|-\n| Luis || Apple, Walnut, Raisin and [[Cheshire cheese|Cheshire Cheese]] [[Turnover (food)|Chaussons]]<br>[[Pain au chocolat|Pain au Chocolat Blanc]] with Raspberries and Cream Cheese || align=\"center\"|2nd || Village in Chocolate\n|- style=\"background:gold\"\n| Nancy || Apple and Lemon Kites<br>Raspberry and Almond Croissants || align=\"center\"|1st || [[Moulin Rouge|Red Windmill]]\n|-\n| Richard || Pear [[Pain au chocolat|Pain au Chocolat]]<br>Pain Au Lait || align=\"center\"|3rd || [[Mill Hill#History|Mill on the Hill]]\n|}\n\n=== Masterclasses ===\nMary and Paul demonstrated how to bake the technical challenges that they set for the bakers as well as their own favorite recipes for some of the other challenges set in the series. They also gave some tips on baking techniques. The Masterclasses episodes were shown on BBC2.\n\n==== Episode 1 ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!  !! Bake 1 !! Bake 2 !! Bake 3\n|-\n| Mary || [[Cherry cake|Cherry Cake]] || [[Florentine biscuit|Florentines]] || Miniature Coffee and Walnut Cakes\n|-\n| Paul || Blackcurrant and Liquorice<br>Swiss Roll || Savoury Biscuits || {{n/a}}\n|}\n\n==== Episode 2 ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!  !! Bake 1 !! Bake 2 !! Bake 3\n|-\n| Mary || Tiramisu Cake || Neapolitan Baked Alaska || {{n/a}}\n|-\n| Paul || Ciabatta ||  Roquefort and Walnut Loaf || Chocolate Volcanoes\n|}\n\n==== Episode 3 ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!  !! Bake 1 !! Bake 2 !! Bake 3\n|-\n| Mary || Chocolate and Orange Tart || Prinsesst\u00e5rta || Almond Praline and Caramel-Coated Hazelnut Dobos Torte\n|-\n| Paul || Mini Sausage Plaits || Kouign-Amann || {{n/a}}\n|}\n\n==== Episode 4 ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!  !! Bake 1 !! Bake 2 !! Bake 3\n|-\n| Mary || Lemon and Raspberry \u00c9clairs<br> || Double Chocolate Mousse Entremets || {{n/a}}\n|-\n| Paul || Chocolate and Cherry Loaf || Povitica || Chocolate and Raspberry Doughnuts\n|}\n\n==== Christmas special ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!  !! Bake 1 !! Bake 2 !! Bake 3\n|-\n| Mary || White Chocolate and Ginger Cheesecake|| [[Genoa Cake]] || Almond [[Galette]]\n|-\n| Paul || [[Saffron bun|St. Lucia Buns]]|| [[Mincemeat]] and [[Marzipan]] Couronne || [[Kransekake]]\n|}\n\n==Controversy==\n\n===\"Bingate\"===\nIn the fourth episode of the series, there was controversy over the events that preceded the elimination of contestant Iain Watters. During the final showstopper round contestants were tasked with producing a baked Alaska. Iain's ice cream was shown as having not set, and in a show of frustration he threw his bake in the bin. The editing of the show suggested that another contestant, Diana Beard, had caused the failure by removing the ice cream from a freezer for her own ice cream, and the perceived \"sabotage\" resulted in a furore on social media networks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/the-great-british-bake-off-rocked-by-baked-alaska-sabotage-scandal-9695831.html |title=Great British Bake Off rocked by Baked Alaska 'sabotage' scandal |publisher=The Independent |date=28 August 2014 |accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref> More than 800 complaints were lodged with the BBC, and some complained to the communication watchdog [[Ofcom]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/aug/29/great-british-bake-off-ofcom-complaints-bbc-diana-beard-iain-watters |title=Great British Bake Off: Ofcom rules out investigation despite complaints |author=Jason Deans |date=29 August 2014 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> Some members of the cast however posted comments in support of Diana,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/aug/28/great-british-bake-off-paul-hollywood-sue-perkins-bingate-iain-watters |title=Great British Bake Off: Paul Hollywood and Sue Perkins speak out on 'bingate' |publisher=guardian.com |date=28 August 2014 |accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref> and a BBC spokesman later issued a statement:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2014/08/28/great-british-bake-off-2014-bbc-receives-over-500-bingate-complaints-while-justiceforiain-dominates-twitter-4849049/ |title=Great British Bake Off 2014: BBC receives over 500 'bingate' complaints while #justiceforiain dominates Twitter |publisher=metro.co.uk |date=28 August 2014 |accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref> \n\n''\"As shown in the episode, Iain became the fourth baker to leave the tent because he didn't present Paul and Mary with anything to judge in the showstopper challenge and both judges were very clear about the reasoning behind the decision. Due to the extreme temperature in the tent that day, many of the bakers struggled to get their ice cream to set as seen in the episode. Diana removing Iain's ice cream from the freezer for less than a minute was in no way responsible for Iain's departure.''\n\nThe claim that his dish was only left out for a short time however was challenged by Iain Watters, saying that it was left long enough to ruin the dessert.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/aug/28/great-british-bake-off-ian-watters-speaks-diana-beard |title=Great British Bake Off: Iain Watters speaks out as Diana Beard quits |author=Hannah Ellis-Petersen |date= 28 August 2014 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> Fellow contestant Jordan Cox criticized the show's production, claiming the freezers were not very good in quality, and were chosen on aesthetic quality only.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s215/great-british-bake-off/news/a593577/jordan-cox-criticises-in-your-face-great-british-bake-off-team.html|title=Jordan Cox criticises \"in your face\" Great British Bake Off team|author = Ryan Love |date=31 August 2014  |work = Digital Spy}}</ref> Diana Beard left the show before the next episode was filmed due to illness.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-08-28/diana-quits-the-great-british-bake-off-2014 |title=Diana quits The Great British Bake Off 2014 |author=Susanna Lazarus|date= 28 August 2014 |work=Radio Times }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/aug/28/diana-beard-quit-bake-off-smell-taste |title=Diana Beard: I quit Bake Off after losing sense of taste and smell |author=Hannah Ellis-Petersen |date= 28 August 2014 |work=The Guardian }}</ref>\n\nBeard later gave an interview to [[BBC Radio Shropshire]], saying: \"I'm disappointed with the way it's been portrayed. I've been stitched up, haven't I? We were 12 amateur bakers, [there's] no prize money involved. Why would I sabotage Iain's Baked Alaska? This has made it look like some cutthroat competition. I think someone's culpable for the editing, really.\" She also said that Iain's ice cream had been out of the freezer for no more than 40 seconds and that her conscience was intact.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28964737|title=Great British Bake Off: Diana Beard's exit announced|date=29 August 2014|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\n===Innuendo===\nA number of viewers complained to the BBC feedback show ''[[Points of View (TV series)|Points of View]]'' in the fifth series about the \"constant smutty remarks\" from the presenters Mel and Sue.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/great-british-bake-off-2014-viewers-complain-about-smutty-innuendos-as-we-pick-the-best-9752461.html |title=Great British Bake Off 2014: Viewers complain about 'smutty' innuendos |work=The Independent |author=Jess Denham |date=24 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/bake-off-2014-from-a-good-forking-to-erect-biscuits--our-favourite-great-british-innuendos-9782163.html |title=Great British Bake Off innuendos: we pick our favourites |author=Matilda Battersby |date=8 October 2014 |work=The Independent }}</ref> This series was seen as having more innuendos than previous ones; some reviewers noted the \"extra pinch of saucy spice\" and \"the increasingly filthy-minded hosts Mel Giedroyc and Sue Perkins\",<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-the-papers-28684187 |date=7 August 2014 |title=Boris Johnson's 'Commons comeback', Bake Off 'smut' and who is James Corden?\n|author= Andy McFarlane |work=BBC }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/tv-radio/reviews/article4168538.ece |title=TV Review: The Great British Bake Off |author=Andrew Billen |date=7 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/showbiz-tv/hot-tv/380749/Great-British-Bake-Off-Paul-Hollywood-and-Mary-Berry-return-for-smuttiest-series-ever |title=Great British Bake Off: Turning up the heat - new series promises to be smuttiest yet |author=Peter Dyke |date= 27 May 2014 |work=The Daily Star}}</ref> and a columnist for the ''Daily Mail'' argued that the \"smutty\" innuendos made the show no longer fit for family entertainment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2768589/Smut-The-ingredient-s-Bake-Off-turn-JEANETTE-KUPFERMANN-says-hit-no-longer-family-entertainment.html |title=Smut: The ingredient that's made Bake Off a turn-off. JEANETTE KUPFERMANN says the hit show is no longer family entertainment |author= Jeanette Kupfermann | work =Daily Mail |date= 24 September 2014 }}</ref> Series 3 winner John Whaite, however, argued that innuendo is part of what made the show a success,<ref>{{citation |url=\nhttps://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11115090/Soggy-bottoms-and-hot-buns-why-the-Bake-Off-thrives-on-innuendo.html |title=Soggy bottoms and hot buns: why the Bake Off thrives on innuendo |author=John Whaite |date= 23 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph }}</ref> while Paul Hollywood described the innuendos as banter in the spirit of the [[Carry On (franchise)|''Carry On'' films]] and is a part of British culture,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/great-british-bake-off/11141937/Great-British-Bake-Off-smut-Its-just-a-bit-of-banter-says-Paul-Hollywood.html |title=Great British Bake Off smut? It's just a bit of banter, says Paul Hollywood |author= Anita Singh |date=6 Oct 2014 |work= Daily Telegraph}}</ref> a view shared by others.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/oct/08/great-british-bake-off-sprinkling-smut-sexual-innuendo |title=Why the Great British Bake Off needs a sprinkling of smut |author=Martin Rowson |work=The Guardian |date= 8 October 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/culture/harrymount/100076314/great-british-bake-off-smut-ooh-matron-why-innuendo-comes-so-easily-for-the-british/ |title=Great British Bake Off smut: Ooh, Matron! Why innuendo comes so easily for the British |author= Harry Mount |date=6 October 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Post-show careers==\nRichard Burr's book on baking, ''BIY: Bake it Yourself'', was released on 16 August 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.westerndailypress.co.uk/Bake-s-Richard-Burr-new-book-BIY-Bake/story-27811512-detail/story.html |title=Great British Bake Off's Richard Burr on his new book BIY: Bake It Yourself|work= Western Daily Press |date= 19 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nLuis Troyano also wrote a book, ''Bake It Great'', released on 20 August 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/extras/indybest/10-best-cookbooks-by-great-british-bake-off-contestants-james-morton-ruby-tandoh-a6680291.html |title=Great British Bake Off: 10 best cookbooks |author=Pippa Bailey Monday |date=5 October 2015 |work=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nChetna Makan has written a baking book ''The Cardamom Trail,'' released on 21 March 2016, as well as a cookbook ''Chai, Chaat & Chutney: A Street Food Journey Through India'', published on 6 July 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/gbbo-semi-finalist-chetna-makan-publish-second-cookbook-490676 |title=GBBO semi-finalist Chetna Makan to publish second cookbook |author=Katherine Cowdrey |date=20 February 2017 |work=The Bookseller}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| url=https://www.octopusbooks.co.uk/books/detail.page?isbn=9781784722876| title=Chai, Chaat & Chutney| publisher=[[Mitchell Beazley]]| accessdate=2017-08-11| website=octopusbooks.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nMartha Collison has written two baking books, ''Twist,'' released on 14 July 2016, and ''Crave'', published 13 July 2017 with Harper Collins. She also has a weekly column with [[Waitrose]] and is a charity ambassador for [[Tearfund]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/you/article-3663981/Bake-s-youngest-contestant-Martha-Collison-creating-cakes-Queen-writing-cookbook.html|title=Bake Off\u2019s youngest contestant Martha Collison on creating cakes|work=Mail Online|access-date=2017-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Ratings==\nThe series started with its highest ratings for its opening episode after its move to BBC One, with over 7 million tuning in according to overnight figures.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/aug/07/great-british-bake-off-bbc1-ratings |title=John Plunkett |date= 7 August 2014 |work=The Guardian }}</ref> This is adjusted to 8.5 million for its 7-day final viewing figure, making this its second most-watched episode after previous year's final.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/ratings/bbc1s-in-the-club-delivers/5076466.article |title=BBC1's In The Club delivers |date= 21 August 2014 |author= Stephen Price|work=Broadcast Now }}</ref> In the fourth episode, 8.1 million watched the original broadcast,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a593041/great-british-bake-off-climbs-to-huge-ratings-of-810m.html |title=Great British Bake Off climbs to huge ratings of 8.10m |author= Tom Eames |date=8 Aug 2014 |work=Digital Spy }}</ref> but the \"bingate\" controversy gained the show a further 2 million viewers on the [[BBC iPlayer]] catch-up service, giving the show the biggest ever audience with 10.248 million viewers for the episode.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/great-british-bake-off/11088494/Great-British-Bake-Off-shock-as-no-one-is-eliminated.html |title=Great British Bake Off shock as no one is eliminated |author=Hannah Furness |date= 10 September 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/great-british-bake-draws-highest-4170904 |title=Great British Bake Off draws highest ever ratings as 10.3 million viewers tune in |author=Nicola Methven |date= 5 September 2014 |work=Mirror }}</ref> The final of the show gained an overnight viewing figure of 12.29 million,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s215/great-british-bake-off/news/a602261/great-british-bake-off-final-is-most-watched-non-sporting-tv-event-of-year.html|title= Great British Bake Off final is most-watched non-sporting TV event of year|author=Ben Lee |date= 9 October 2014 |work=Digital Spy }}</ref> and a consolidated average figure of 13.5 million, the highest viewing figure for a non-sporting event of the year on UK TV, after [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]'s England vs Uruguay match.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/dec/17/the-great-british-bake-off-tv-ratings-2014 |title=The Great British Bake Off rises to top of most-watched TV of 2014 so far |author=Tara Conlan|date= 17 December 2014 |work=Guardian }}</ref> Series 5 had an average of viewing figure of 10.1 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/ratings/bbc1-rises-to-the-challenge/5082034.article |title=BBC1 rises to the challenge|date=22 January 2015 |author= Stephen Price |work=Broadcast }}</ref>\n\nOfficial episode viewing figures are from [[BARB]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-30|title=Weekly Top 30 Programmes|publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]]|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Episode<br />no. !! Airdate !! Viewers<br /><small>(millions)</small> !! BBC One<br />weekly ranking !! Weekly ranking<br />all channels<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-10?_s=4|title=Weekly Top 10 Programmes|publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]]|accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1 || {{Start date|2014|08|06|df=y}} || 8.51 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| 2 || {{Start date|2014|08|13|df=y}} || 8.79 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| 3 || {{Start date|2014|08|20|df=y}} || 9.28 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| 4 || {{Start date|2014|08|27|df=y}} || 10.25 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| 5 || {{Start date|2014|09|03|df=y}} || 9.95 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| 6 || {{Start date|2014|09|10|df=y}} || 10.13 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| 7 || {{Start date|2014|09|17|df=y}} || 10.28 || 1 || 2\n|-\n| 8 || {{Start date|2014|09|24|df=y}} || 9.02{{ref|3|3}} || 2 || 4\n|-\n| 9 || {{Start date|2014|10|01|df=y}} || 10.67 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| 10 || {{Start date|2014|10|08|df=y}} || 13.51 || 1 || 1\n|}\n<sup>{{note|3|Note 3}}</sup> The programme was rescheduled to BBC Two in Scotland due to a football game.\n\n===Specials===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Episode<br />no. !! Airdate !! Viewers<br /><small>(millions)</small> !! BBC Two<br />weekly ranking\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\"| The Great British Bake Off Masterclass\n|-\n| 1 || {{Start date|2014|10|09|df=y}} || 1.99 || 12\n|-\n| 2 || {{Start date|2014|10|10|df=y}} || 1.53 || 24\n|-\n| 3 || {{Start date|2014|10|15|df=y}} || 2.16 || 7\n|-\n| 4 || {{Start date|2014|10|16|df=y}} || 1.42 || 23\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\"| The Great British Bake Off, Class of 2013\n|-\n| style=\"background:silver;\"| || {{Start date|2014|10|12|df=y}} || {{N/A}} || {{N/A}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\"| The Great British Bake Off, Christmas Masterclass\n|-\n| style=\"background:silver;\"| || {{Start date|2014|12|16|df=y}} || 3.03 || 5\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n\n{{The Great British Bake Off}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Great British Bake Off, The}}\n[[Category:The Great British Bake Off|Series 5]]\n[[Category:British cooking television programmes]]\n[[Category:BBC Television programmes]]\n[[Category:2014 British television seasons]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Fifth series of The Great British Bake Off}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox television season\n| season_number        = 5\n| starring             = \n{{Plainlist|\n* [[Mel Giedroyc]]\n* [[Sue Perkins]]\n* [[Mary Berry]]\n* [[Paul Hollywood]]\n}}\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| num_episodes         = 10\n| network              = [[BBC One]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|2014|8|06|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = {{start date|2014|10|08|df=y}}\n}}\n\nThe '''fifth series''' of ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]'' began on Wednesday 6 August 2014.<ref name=\"digital\">{{cite news |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s215/great-british-bake-off/news/a585984/fire-up-your-ovens-the-great-british-bake-off-return-date-confirmed.html#~oL11ELb7S7EU2j |title= Fire up your ovens! The Great British Bake Off return date confirmed |work=Digital Spy |date=23 July 2014  |author= Sam Rigby }}</ref> [[Mel Giedroyc]] and [[Sue Perkins]] presented the show and [[Mary Berry]] and [[Paul Hollywood]] returned as judges.  Twelve contestants competed in this series, and the competition was held in [[Welford Park]] in Berkshire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-08-06/bake-off-insiders-reveal-what-really-goes-on-inside-the-tent |title=Bake Off insiders reveal what really goes on inside the tent |author=Rosie Millard|date=6 August 2014 |work=Radio Times }}</ref> The series was won by [[Nancy Birtwhistle]], with Luis Troyano and Richard Burr finishing as runners-up.\n\nThe programme was moved from [[BBC Two]] to [[BBC One]] starting this year, however the Masterclass episodes remained on BBC Two.  A companion series ''[[The Great British Bake Off: An Extra Slice]]'' hosted by comedian [[Jo Brand]] started this year was also shown on BBC Two.\n\n== Bakers ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Baker<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/4fB8YW68M3BX4LVd9XkRGxv/bakers |title=Bakers |work=BBC |date=29 July 2014}}</ref>!! Age !! Occupation !! Hometown !! links\n|-\n| Chetna Makan ||align=\"center\"| 35 || Fashion Designer ||[[Broadstairs]], Kent ||<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thanetgazette.co.uk/Chetna-Makan-shines-Great-British-Bake/story-22123450-detail/story.html |title=Chetna Makan shines on Great British Bake Off |author= David Archer  | date= 6 August 2014 |work = Isle of Thanet Gazette }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://chetnamakan.co.uk/chetna/ |title=Chetna Makan: About Me |author=Chetna Makan}}</ref>\n|-\n| Claire Goodwin || align=\"center\"|31 || Speech Therapist ||[[Ashton upon Mersey]], [[Trafford]] || <ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/in-your-area/trafford-speech-therapist-bake-star-7568644 |title=Speech therapist to be Bake Off star |date=5 August 2014 |author= Helen Johnson |work=Manchester Evening News }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://baketherapy.co.uk/ |title=Claire Goodwin's Bake Therapy Bake You Better |author=Clair Goodwin}}</ref>\n|-\n| Diana Beard || alig