t|UKR&B|12|date=2001-07-07}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{albumchart|Billboard200|1|artist=Snoop Dogg|album=Doggystyle|accessdate=May 29, 2014|refname=\"US200\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{albumchart|BillboardRandBHipHop|1|artist=Snoop Dogg|album=Doggystyle|accessdate=May 29, 2014|refname=\"USR&BAl\"}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n=== Catalog charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (1997\u20132015)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{albumchart|BillboardCatalog|7|artist=Snoop Dogg|album=Doggystyle}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard charts|R&B/Hip-Hop Catalog Albums]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web | url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Snoop Dogg|chart=R&B/Hip-Hop Catalog Albums}} | title=Snoop Doggy Dogg \u2013 Chart History: R&B/Hip-Hop Catalog Albums | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (1994)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/1994/the-billboard-200|title=Billboard 200 albums year end 1994|author=|date=|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|US [[Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=Top+R%26B/Hip-Hop+Albums&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1994|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211065742/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=Top+R%26B%2FHip-Hop+Albums&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1994|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-12-11|title=Billboard Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums year end 1994|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=2009-09-08}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (1995)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|US [[Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web|URL=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/1995/top-r-b-hip-hop-albums|title=Billboard Top R&B/Hip Hop Albums year end 1995|author=|date=|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|100\n|}\n\n===End of decade charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (1990\u20131999)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"1990sbb\">{{Cite book | author = Geoff Mayfield | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&lr&rview=1&pg=RA1-PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false | title = 1999 The Year in Music Totally '90s: Diary of a Decade - The listing of Top Pop Albums of the '90s & Hot 100 Singles of the '90s | publisher = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date = December 25, 1999 | accessdate = October 15, 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|64\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|award=Platinum|relyear=1993|certyear=1994|artist=Snoop Dogg|type=album|title=Doggystyle}}\n\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|award=Gold|relyear=1993|certyear=1996|artist=Snoop Dogg|type=album|title=Doggystyle}}\n\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|award=Platinum|relyear=1993|certyear=2013|artist=Snoop Dogg|type=album|title=Doggystyle}}\n\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|award=Platinum|number=4 |relyear=1993|certyear=1994|salesamount= 6,957,800|artist=Snoop Dogg|type=album|title=Doggystyle|refname=\"RIAA\"|salesref=<ref name=\"Sales\"/>}}\n\n{{Certification Table Summary}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Worldwide|nocert=true|relyear=1993|salesamount=11,000,000|salesref=<ref name=\"Sales\"/>|artist=Snoop Dogg|type=album|title=Doggystyle}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Region\n! Date\n! Format(s)\n! Label\n! Ref.\n|- \n| rowspan=\"2\" | United States\n| November 10, 1993\n| [[compact Cassette|cassette]]\n| [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Snoop-Doggy-Dogg-Doggystyle/release/7330178|title=Snoop Doggy Dogg* \u2013 Doggystyle (cassette)|publisher=[[Discogs]] (US)|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 23, 1993\n| {{hlist|[[Compact disc|CD]]|[[LP record|LP]]}}\n| {{hlist|[[Death Row Records|Death Row]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Snoop-Doggy-Dogg-Doggystyle/release/829287|title=Snoop Doggy Dogg* \u2013 Doggystyle (CD, LP)|publisher=[[Discogs]] (US)|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of hip hop albums considered to be influential]]\n*[[List of number-one albums of 1993 (U.S.)]]\n*[[List of number-one albums of 1994 (U.S.)]]\n*[[List of number-one R&B albums of 1993 (U.S.)]]\n*[[List of number-one R&B albums of 1994 (U.S.)]]\n*[[Billboard Year-End]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Snoop Dogg}}\n\n[[Category:1993 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Death Row Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dr. Dre]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records albums]]\n[[Category:Snoop Dogg albums]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rap albums by American artists]]\n[[Category:G-funk albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Snoop Dogg album|other uses|Doggy style (disambiguation)}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Doggystyle\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Snoop Dogg|Snoop Doggy Dogg]]\n| cover      = [[File:Doggystyle.jpg|thumb|Doggystyle album cover]]\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 23, 1993\n| recorded   = January \u2013 October 1993\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{hlist|[[The Village (studio)|The Village Recorder]] in [[West Los Angeles]]|The Complex Studios in [[Los Angeles]]|Larrabee North studios and Larrabee West studios in [[North Hollywood]]}}\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[West Coast hip hop]]|[[G-funk]]|[[gangsta rap]]}}\n| length     = 55:05\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Death Row Records|Death Row]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Dr. Dre]]|[[Suge Knight]] <small>(exec.)}}\n| prev_title = \n| prev_year  = \n| next_title = [[Tha Doggfather]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Doggystyle\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[What's My Name? (Snoop Doggy Dogg song)|Who Am I? (What's My Name?)]]\n | single1date = October 30, 1993\n | single2     = [[Gin and Juice|Gin & Juice]]\n | single2date = January 15, 1994\n | single3     = [[Doggy Dogg World]]\n | single3date = June 26, 1994\n}}\n}}\n'''''Doggystyle''''' is the debut studio album by American rapper [[Snoop Dogg|Snoop Doggy Dogg]]. It was released on November 23, 1993, by [[Death Row Records]] and [[Interscope Records]]. The album was recorded and produced following Snoop's appearances on [[Dr. Dre]]'s debut solo album ''[[The Chronic]]'' (1992), to which Snoop contributed significantly. The West Coast style in hip-hop that he developed from Dre's first album continued on ''Doggystyle''.<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/doggystyle-mw0000106179 | title=Doggystyle \u2013 Snoop Dogg | publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]] | work=[[AllMusic]] | access-date=May 29, 2014 | author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas | authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine}}</ref> Critics have praised Snoop Doggy Dogg for the lyrical \"realism\" that he delivers on the album and for his distinctive vocal flow.<ref name=AMG/><ref name=AMG-Bio/> Despite some mixed criticism of the album initially upon its release, ''Doggystyle'' earned recognition from many music critics as one of the most significant albums of the 1990s, as well as one of the most important hip-hop albums ever released.<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/> Much like ''The Chronic'', the distinctive sounds of ''Doggystyle'' helped introduce the hip-hop subgenre of g-funk to a mainstream audience, bringing forward [[West Coast hip hop]] as a dominant force in the early-mid 1990s.<ref name=AMG/><ref name=AMG-TheChronic/>\n\n''Doggystyle'' debuted at No. 1 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling 806,858 copies in its first week alone in the United States, which was the record for a debuting artist and the fastest-selling hip-hop album ever. ''Doggystyle'' was included on The Source magazine's list of the 100 Best Rap Albums; as well as ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's list of Essential Recordings of the '90s.<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/> About.com placed the album in No. 17 of the greatest hip hop/rap albums of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rap.about.com/od/toppicks/ss/Top100RapAlbums_9.htm |title=The Greatest Hip-Hop Albums of all Time - Top 100 Rap/Hip-Hop Albums |publisher=Rap.about.com |date=2010-04-07 |accessdate=2010-05-18}}</ref> The album was certified quadruple [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). By November 2015, the album had sold 7 million copies in the United States, and over 11 million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"Sales\">{{cite magazine|url=http://thesource.com/2015/11/23/today-in-hip-hop-history-snoop-dogg-releases-his-debut-album-doggystyle-22-years-ago/ |title=Today in Hip Hop History: Snoop Dogg Releases His Debut Album 'Doggystyle' 22 Years Ago |magazine=[[The Source]] |date=November 23, 2015 |accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Sales2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yardbarker.com/entertainment/articles/doggystyle_turns_25_snoop_dogg_secures_his_place_in_hip_hop_with_a_g_funk_sound/s1_13132_27832094 |title=\n\u2018Doggystyle\u2019 turns 25: Snoop Dogg secures his place in hip-hop with a G-Funk sound|publisher=yardbarker |date=November 21, 2018 |accessdate=November 22, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Conception ==\n=== Background ===\nIn 1992, Snoop Doggy Dogg came to attention of the music industry through his vocal contributions on Dr. Dre's ''The Chronic''. That album is considered to have \"transformed the entire sound of West Coast rap\" by its development of what later became known as the \"[[G-funk]]\" sound.<ref name=AMG-TheChronic>Steve Huey. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r814133|pure_url=yes}} The Chronic > Overview]. Allmusic. Accessed May 17, 2008.</ref> ''The Chronic'' expanded [[gangsta rap]] with profanity, anti-authoritarian lyrics and multi-layered [[Sampling (music)|samples]] taken from 1970's [[P-Funk]] records.<ref name=AMG-TheChronic/> Snoop Doggy Dogg contributed vocals to Dre's solo single, \"[[Deep Cover (song)|Deep Cover]]\", which led to a high degree of anticipation among hip hop for the release of his own solo album.<ref name=AMG-Bio/>\n\n''Doggystyle'' and ''The Chronic'' are associated with each other mainly because each prominently featured Snoop Dogg and because both contain G-funk style production from Dr. Dre. The two releases are linked by the high number of vocal contributions from Death Row Records artists, including [[Tha Dogg Pound]], [[RBX]], [[The Lady of Rage]],<ref name=TheSource/> while both contain a high density of misogynistic lyrics and profanity in their lyrics.<ref name=Stylus-TheChronicVsDoggystyle/> In addition, the two albums are each viewed by critics as early \"G-funk classics\", and have been described as  \"joined at the hip\". 'Doggystyle' also marked the debut of Death Row vocalist, Nanci Fletcher - the daughter of jazz legend Sam Fletcher.<ref name=AMG/><ref name=Stylus-TheChronicVsDoggystyle/>\n\n[[Gangsta rap]] has been criticized for its extreme lyrics, which are often accused of glamorizing gang violence and black-on-black crime. The Gangsta rappers responded that they were simply describing the realities of life in places such as [[Compton, California]], and [[Long Beach, California]].<ref name=AMG-SOC>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/straight-outta-compton-mw0000653426 | title=Straight Outta Compton \u2013 N.W.A. | publisher=Rovi Corporation | work=AllMusic | accessdate=May 29, 2014 | author=Henderson, Alex}}</ref><ref name=Davemusic>Reference to Alex Henderson's Allmusic review on Dave's music database: [http://whitgunn.freeservers.com/Davemusic/N/NWA/straight-outta-compton.html Straight Outta Compton Reviews]</ref> Describing ''Doggystyle'' in 1993, Snoop Doggy Dogg likewise points to the album's realism, and the extent to which it is based on his personal experience.  He said, \"I can't rap about something I don't know. You'll never hear me rapping about no bachelor's degree. It's only what I know and that's that street life. It's all everyday life, reality.\"<ref name=NYTimes-PopMusic/> Explaining his intentions, Snoop Doggy Dogg claims he feels he is a role model to many young black men, and that his songs are designed to relate to their concerns. \"For little kids growing up in the ghettos,\" he said, \"it's easy to get into the wrong types of things, especially gangbanging and selling drugs. I've seen what that was like, and I don't glorify it, but I don't preach. I bring it to them rather than have them go find out about it for themselves.\"<ref name=NYTimes-PopMusic/> He further explained the \"dream\" that he would pursue after making the album: \"I'm going to try to eliminate the gang violence. I'll be on a mission for peace. I know I have a lot of power. I know if I say, 'Don't kill', niggas won't kill\".<ref name=NYTimes-PopMusic>Tour\u00e9 (November 21, 1993). [https://www.nytimes.com/1993/11/21/arts/pop-music-snoop-dogg-s-gentle-hip-hop-growl.html?pagewanted=3 Pop Music; Snoop Dogg's Gentle Hip-Hop Growl]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved April 21, 2008. {{Cite web |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CEFDB133DF932A15752C1A965958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=3 |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 21, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516165521/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CEFDB133DF932A15752C1A965958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=3 |archive-date=May 16, 2008 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Recording ===\n[[File:Snoop Dogg Hawaii.jpg|thumb|Snoop Dogg (formerly known as Snoop Doggy Dogg) (pictured in 2005) wrote the majority of ''Doggystyle'' while in the studio.]]\n''Doggystyle'' was recorded in early-1993 at [[Death Row Records|Death Row Studios]]. It was produced in a style similar to ''The Chronic''; some critics called it a \"carbon copy\".<ref name=AMG-Bio/> Snoop Doggy Dogg collaborated with two music groups, [[213 (group)|213]] and [[Tha Dogg Pound]]. Daz Dillinger, of the latter group, accused Dr. Dre of taking sole recognition for producing the album and alleged that [[Warren G]] and himself contributed substantially to the production of the project.<ref name=DPG-Eulogy>Tha Dogg Pound. (2005). ''[[DPG Eulogy]]'' [DVD]. Innovative Distribution Network. Retrieved April 27, 2008.</ref> Death Row Records co-founder [[Marion \"Suge\" Knight]] stated in 2013 that, \"Daz pretty much did the whole album\", and that credit was signed over to Dr. Dre for a fee.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Paul |last=Cantor |date=November 25, 2013 |title=Suge Knight Reflects on 'Doggystyle' 20 Years Later |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/suge-knight-reflects-on-doggystyle-20-years-later-20131125 |accessdate=November 25, 2013 }}</ref> Snoop Doggy Dogg said Dr. Dre was capable of making beats without the help of collaborators and addressed the issues with Warren G and Daz, stating \"They made beats, Dre produced that record\". He discussed the track \"Ain't No Fun\", mentioning that Daz and Warren G brought Dr. Dre the beat but \"Dre took that muthafucka to the next level!\"<ref name=DubCNN-Interview>[http://www.dubcnn.com/interviews/snoopdogg06/part4/ Snoop Dogg Interview Part 4 (July 2006)]. DubCNN. Retrieved April 27, 2008.</ref> Bruce Williams, closely affiliated with Dr. Dre, discussed the recording process during Dre's time at Death Row Records, stating:\n\n{{quote|Dre's going to be the first one in the studio and the last one to leave. He'll start messing with a beat. As the beat starts pumping, the guys start filtering in. Everybody will get their little drink and smoke in. Soon enough, the beat starts to make a presence. You'll look around the room and every cat that was a rapper \u2013 from Kurupt to Daz to Snoop \u2013 will grab a pen. They would start writing while Dre is making a beat so by the time he's finished with the beat, they are ready to hit the booth and start spittin'. To see those young cats \u2013 they were all hungry and wanted to make something dope. The atmosphere that was there, you couldn't be wack.<ref name=HipHopDX/>}}\n\nWilliams said the album was never finished and because of the demand for the record, the distributors insisted the album be completed, otherwise they would cancel the album's orders. This resulted in Dr. Dre mixing the album and inserting the skits within 48 hours, which enabled the album to be released.<ref name=HipHopDX>Andreas Hale (May 21, 2008). [http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/features/id.1126/title./p.2 Bruce Williams: The REAL Doctor's Advocate Pt 1]. HipHopDX. Accessed May 26, 2008.</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' writer Jonathan Gold described how Dr. Dre produced a beat from scratch to complete instrumental: \"Dre may find something he likes from an old drum break, loop it and gradually replace each part with a better tom-tom sound, a kick-drum sound he adores, until the beat bears the same relationship to the original that the Incredible Hulk does to Bill Bixby\".<ref name=RS-DayOfTheDre>Jonathan Gold (September 30, 1993). [https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/drdre/articles/story/5937496/cover_story_day_of_the_dre Day of the Dre]. ''Rolling Stone''. Accessed May 27, 2008. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506072416/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/drdre/articles/story/5937496/cover_story_day_of_the_dre |date=May 6, 2008 }}</ref> Gold also described how the track progressed with other musicians adding to the song, stating \"A bass player wanders in, unpacks his instrument and pops a funky two-note bass line over the beat, then leaves to watch CNN, though his two notes keep looping into infinity. A smiling guy in a striped jersey plays a nasty one-fingered melody on an old [[Minimoog]] synthesizer that's been obsolete since 1982, and Dre scratches in a sort of surfadelic munching noise, and then from his well-stocked [[Akai MPC60]] samples comes a shriek, a spare piano chord, an ejaculation from the first [[Beastie Boys|Beastie's]] [[Licensed to Ill|record]] -- \"Let me clear my throat\"\u2014and the many-layered groove is happening, bumping, breathing, almost loud enough to see.\"<ref name=RS-DayOfTheDre/>\n\nWhile recording ''Doggystyle'' with Dr. Dre in August 1993, Snoop Dogg was arrested in connection with the death of Phillip Woldermarian, a member of a rival gang who was shot and killed in a gang fight. According to the charges, the rapper's bodyguard, McKinley Lee, shot Woldermarian as Snoop Dogg drove the vehicle; the rapper claimed it was self-defense, alleging the victim was stalking him. He spent most of 1995 preparing the case which went to trial in late-1995. He was cleared of all charges in February 1996 when he began working on his second album, ''[[Tha Doggfather]]''.<ref name=AMG-Bio>Stephen Thomas Erlewine. [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p41625|pure_url=yes}} Snoop Dogg > Biography]. Allmusic. Retrieved April 21, 2008.</ref>\n\n=== Title significance ===\nThe album's title alludes to the [[doggy style]] sex position and is a reference to the musician's name. The artwork, which was done by artist Joe Cool, represents the themes covered in the album and the style of implementation of those ideas. Some critics believe the artwork portrays a woman merely as a hole to be filled by the man, which they believe adheres to the narcissistic and sexist lyrical themes Snoop Dogg covers.<ref name=Rap-BlackRage>Steven Best & Douglas Kellner. [http://enculturation.gmu.edu/2_2/best-kellner.html Rap, Black Rage, and Racial Difference] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513135846/http://enculturation.gmu.edu/2_2/best-kellner.html |date=May 13, 2008 }}. ''Enculturation'', Vol. 2, No. 2, Spring 1999. Accessed May 27, 2008.</ref> In this interpretation, the cover art and lyrics convey what they refer to as the self-indulgent \"gangsta\" lifestyle, drugs, cars, sex, and money.<ref name=Rap-BlackRage/> The artwork uses several quotes from the 1982 [[George Clinton (funk musician)|George Clinton]] single \"[[Atomic Dog]]\". The quotes come from the dogs at the top of the brick wall on the album cover, which say, \"Why must I feel like dat?\", \"Why must I chase da cat?\" and \"Nuttin' but da dogg in me\".<ref name=MTV-Lyrics>[http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/clinton_george/1954211/lyrics.jhtml George Clinton's Atomic Dog Lyrics]. [[MTV Networks]]. Retrieved June 4, 2008.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514041717/http://www.mtv.com/music/artist/clinton_george/1954211/lyrics.jhtml |date=May 14, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n\n=== Production ===\n[[File:Dr. Dre.jpg|thumb|Snoop collaborated with fellow hitmaker [[Dr. Dre]] (''pictured in 2008'') on the album production.]]\n\nDre's handling of the production was praised by critics. [[AllMusic]] writer [[Stephen Erlewine]] stated: \"Dre realized that it wasn't time to push the limits of G-funk, and instead decided to deepen it musically, creating easy-rolling productions that have more layers than they appear\". He added that the beats were \"laid-back funky, continuing to resonate after many listens\".<ref name=AMG/> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' writer [[Tour\u00e9]] noted \"''The Chronic''{{'}}s slow, heavy beats were a sonic representation of angry depression as accurate as [[Kurt Cobain|Cobain]]'s feedback blasts; ''Doggystyle'' is leaner, with its high-tempo [[Isaac Hayes]]- and [[Curtis Mayfield]]-derived tracks\". He went on to say that \"Most of Dre's hooks and nearly all his beats refuse to linger, as if the songs themselves are nervous, fearful of exposure, restless to get offscreen.\"<ref name=RollingStone/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' magazine's David Browne mentioned that \"The mix of samples and live music on Dre's latest, ''The Chronic'', gave it texture and depth, and he continues his knob-turning growth on ''Doggystyle'', fluidly weaving together a gaggle of background singers and rappers, quirky samples, his trademark horror-flick keyboard lines\".<ref name=EW/> The Source magazine columinst wrote: \"Dre's brand of G-funk may be common now, but it is still painstakingly well-produced\".<ref name=TheSource/>\n\n=== Lyrics ===\nSnoop Doggy Dogg's lyrics were generally praised by critics, although they caused some controversy. He was acclaimed for the realism in his rhymes and his harmonious flow.<ref name=AMG/><ref name=AMG-Bio/> AllMusic's Stephen Erlewine commended Snoop Doggy Dogg, saying: \"he's one of hip-hop's greatest vocal stylists with this record\" and he \"takes his time, playing with the flow of his words, giving his rhymes a nearly melodic eloquence. Snoop is something special, with unpredictable turns of phrase, evocative imagery, and a distinctive, addictive flow\".<ref name=AMG/> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's Christopher John Farley noted \"Snoop's rapping isn't flashy, but it is catchy\" and stated \"His relaxed vocal style is a perfect match for Dre's bass-heavy producing. Snoop's voice is lithe enough to snake its way around the big beats,\" said Farley on November 29, 1993.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,979677,00.html Gangsta Rap, Doggystyle]. ''Time''. Retrieved April 19, 2008.</ref> The ideas put forward through the lyrics include Snoop Doggy Dogg's adolescent urges, as he freely talks of casual sex, smoking [[cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] and gunning down rival gang members. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine remarked that the notions \"are often unnecessarily graphic; at some points they're downright obscene\" and that \"the album would have been stronger if such misgivings about the criminal life, as well as Snoop's touches of introspection, had been applied to some of the cruder songs\".<ref name=Time>Christopher John Farley (November 29, 1993). [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,979677,00.html Gangsta Rap, Doggystyle]. ''Time''. Retrieved April 19, 2008.</ref> The album also covered gun play, drug dealing and pimping. ''[[The New York Times]]'' said that the lyrical concepts were delivered in \"crudest, rudest terms\".<ref name=NewYorkTimes>Jon Pareles (October 31, 1995). [https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/31/arts/critic-s-notebook-rappers-making-notoriety-pay-off.html?sq=Doggystyle+1993&scp=8&st=nyt Critic's Notebook; Rappers Making Notoriety Pay Off]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved April 19, 2008.</ref>\n\nSome critics said Snoop Doggy Dogg was \"obsessed with being a 'G', a gangster, a lawbreaker who smokes dope and kills with impunity\" and that his lyrics depict the black-on-black crime in the inner-cities.<ref name=Rap-BlackRage/> The lyrics involve many derogatory terms against women, with expressions such as \"bitches\" and \"hoes\" being used throughout, which illustrates the feeling of sexism and oppression within American society.<ref name=Rap-BlackRage/> In certain tracks Snoop Doggy Dogg and Tha Dogg Pound casually speak of group sex, illustrating the demeaning of women.<ref name=Journal>Edward G. Armstrong. [http://www.uri.edu/artsci/ecn/starkey/ECN386%20-Race,Gender,%20Class/gangsta_Misogyny.pdf Gangsta Misogyny: A Content Analysis Of The Portrayals Of Violence Against Women In Rap Music]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528033323/http://www.uri.edu/artsci/ecn/starkey/ECN386%20-Race%2CGender%2C%20Class/gangsta_Misogyny.pdf |date=May 28, 2008 }}. ''Journal of Criminal Justice and Popular Culture'', Vol. 8, Issue 2 (2001) pp. 96\u2013126. Accessed May 27, 2008.</ref> Snoop Doggy Dogg's lyrics depict drugs, alcohol, sex, and money as methods of escape from oppression, but they also show an underside of the \"gangsta\" lifestyle and the results of following this lifestyle.<ref name=Rap-BlackRage/> The lyrics' violent representations, including murder and aggressive behaviour, have also generated controversy. C. DeLores Tucker of the National Political Congress of Black Women named gangsta rap \"a profane and obscene glorification of murder and rape\", which can be attributed to ''Doggystyle''.<ref name=Journal/>\n\n=== Content ===\n{| border=\"0\"  style=\"float:right; font-size:100%; color:black; width:130px;\"\n|-\n|\n{{Listen|pos = right\n |filename     = Snoop Dogg - Who Am I (What's My Name) ?.ogg\n |title        = \"Who Am I (What's My Name)?\" 11\n |description  = The song features Snoop Dogg's rhyming style and flow, as well as his early work with G-Funk production.\n |filename2    = Snoop Doggy Dogg - Gin and Juice.ogg\n |title2       = \"Gin and Juice\"\n |description2 = One of Snoop Dogg's most famous songs, [[Gin and Juice]]'s lyrical content depict a party filled with [[Sexual intercourse|sex]], [[marijuana]], and [[alcohol (drug)|alcohol]].\n}}\n|}\n\n\"Who Am I (What's My Name)?\" was the first single released from the album, on October 30, 1993. It peaked at No. 8 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks]] charts, and reached No. 1 on the [[Hot Rap Singles]]. It is largely recognised as the album's 'leading single', and the RIAA certified it [[RIAA certification|Gold]] on February 8, 1994.  It was certified Platinum later the same year.<ref name=RIAA-Singles>[https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Snoop%20Dogg&format=single&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2007&sort=Artist&perPage=25 RIAA Searchable database - Snoop Dogg Singles] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017084407/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Snoop%20Dogg&format=single&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2007&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |date=October 17, 2015 }}. Recording Industry Association of America. Retrieved April 19, 2008.</ref> It reached No. 20 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] in 1994 and re-entered the chart in 2004, reaching No. 100.<ref name=EveryHit>[http://www.everyhit.com/ UK Top 40 Hit Database]. everyHit.com. Accessed April 20, 2008. Note: User must define search parameters, i.e. \"Snoop Dogg\".</ref><ref name=ChartsPlus>[http://www.chartsplus.co.uk/ChartsPlus172.pdf UK Single Charts]. ChartsPlus. Retrieved April 19, 2008.</ref> In terms of critical reception and the volume of sales, it is Snoop's most successful single to date. \"Gin and Juice\" was the second single released on January 15, 1994. Like the previous single, it was a hit on multiple charts. It reached No. 8 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], No. 13 on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks]], No. 1 on [[Hot Rap Singles]], and No. 39 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=EveryHit/><ref name=AMG-Singles/> The RIAA certified it Platinum on April 6, 1994.<ref name=RIAA-Singles/> The song was nominated at the [[Grammy Awards of 1995|1995 Grammy Awards]] for [[Best Rap Solo Performance]], but lost to [[Queen Latifah]]'s \"[[U.N.I.T.Y.]]\". \"Doggy Dogg World\" was released as a Europe-only single during June 1994. Even though the single was not officially released in the U.S., it received some radio airplay which resulted in position 19 on the Rhythmic Top&nbsp;40 chart.<ref name=AMG-Singles/> A music video was produced for the single, which gained American video TV-play and won the 1994 [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Rap Video]]. It reached No. 32 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=EveryHit/>\n\n\"Lodi Dodi\" and \"Murder Was the Case\" were not official singles, but they received radio airplay and charted in [[Rhythmic Top 40]].<ref name=AMG-Singles>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p41625|pure_url=yes}} Doggystyle - Billboard Singles]. Allmusic. Retrieved April 19, 2008.</ref> An 18-minute music video was shot for the two songs, with an accompanying ''[[Murder Was the Case]]'' soundtrack.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">David Browne (February 3, 1995). [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,296002,00.html Murder Was the Case: The Movie]. ''Entertainment Weekly''. Retrieved June 4, 2008.</ref> The video won the 1995 Video of the Year award at [[The Source (magazine)|The Source]] Hip-Hop Music Awards. \"Gin and Juice\" was nominated at the [[Grammy Awards of 1995|1995 Grammy Awards]] for [[Best Rap Solo Performance]]. A bonus track, \"Gz Up, Hoes Down\", was included in the album's first pressing, but not in later versions because of sample clearance issues. Snoop Doggy Dogg could not gain the rights to use the beats because the record company was not willing to pay license fees for using the samples.<ref name=SnoopDogg>[http://www.snoop-dogg.com/doggystyle19.php Snoop Dogg Lyrics, Pictures, Albums and more]. Snoop-Dogg.com. Retrieved April 20, 2008.</ref> \"Gz Up, Hoes Down\" was later released on the Death Row compilation \"[[15 Years on Death Row]]\". \"Tha Next Episode\" was listed on the cover, but not included in any pressing. It is considered the original material used for the 2000 Dr. Dre single \"[[The Next Episode]]\" but bears no resemblance to the later song. It was 4&nbsp;minutes and 36&nbsp;seconds (4:36) long.<ref name=DubCNN>[http://www.dubcnn.com/reviews/doggystyle Album Analysis]. DubCNN.com. Retrieved April 20, 2008.</ref> \"Tha Next Episode\" was later released on the Dr. Dre mixtape ''Pretox'' under the name \"Chronic Unreleased Studio Session\", but only 1:10 long. \"Doggystyle\" featuring [[George Clinton (funk musician)|George Clinton]] was a 5:26 long outtake from the album sessions. It is a singing melody with vocals dominating the song and it extensively samples \"Oh I\" by Funkadelic from their album ''[[The Electric Spanking of War Babies]]''.  Jewell & The Brides of Funkenstein are featured on the chorus.<ref name=DubCNN/>  The song was released on ''[[Death Row: The Lost Sessions Vol. 1]]'' amongst other songs recorded by Snoop Doggy Dogg during his tenure at Death Row.\n\n== Legacy and influence==\n\n=== Hip-hop music ===\n''Doggystyle'' is seen by many hip hop pundits as a \"classic\" and an \"essential\" album.<ref name=About>[http://rap.about.com/od/top10albums/ss/EssentialAlbums.htm 10 Essential Hip-Hop Albums]. About. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref> It is credited with defining [[West Coast hip hop]]; shifting the emphasis to more melodious, synth-driven, and funk-induced beats. About.com stated during the period the album was released, \"Gangsta rap never sounded so sweet.\" The album is credited for further establishment of the slurred \"lazy drawl\" that sacrificed lyrical complexity for clarity and [[rhythm]]ic [[Cadence (music)|cadence]] on ''Doggystyle'' and ''The Chronic''.<ref name=AMG/><ref name=AMG-Bio/> The album is considered as one of the first G-funk albums the style of which many rappers duplicated in later years.<ref name=AMG/>\n\n=== Hip-hop culture ===\nIt has been suggested by some writers and publications that ''Doggystyle'' has considerably affected African-American culture. Some publications have held the rap genre responsible for social problems such as sexual violence and sexism, which has been blamed on Snoop Doggy Dogg and other rappers for calling their controversial lyrics \"keeping it real.\"<ref name=PimpsUpHosDown>T. Denean. (2007). ''Pimps Up, Ho's Down: Hip Hop's Hold on Young Black Women''. pp. 12\u201315. New York: NYU Press. {{ISBN|0-8147-4014-6}}.</ref> The problems of sexual violence and sexism are attributed to lyrics degrading women such as \"bitches\" and \"ho's,\" which some believe have influenced black males.<ref name=Rap-BlackRage/><ref name=AACulture>Kevern Verney. (2003). ''African Americans and US Popular Culture ''. pp. 96\u201397. Routledge. {{ISBN|0-415-27527-X}}</ref> Snoop Doggy Dogg and other hip hop artists, including [[N.W.A]], especially [[Eazy-E]], [[Dr. Dre]] and [[Ice Cube]] (due to their success) and [[Tupac Shakur]], have been held accountable for developing the gangsta rap form; a genre which articulated the rage of the urban underclass and its sense of intense oppression and defiant rebellion,<ref name=Rap-BlackRage/> which has been attained through the ability to communicate free of censorship, and has allowed hip hop culture to become a dominant style and ethos throughout the world.<ref name=Rap-BlackRage/> [[Mariah Carey]] sampled the song \"Ain't No Fun (If the Homies Can't Have None)\" in her 1999 album ''[[Rainbow (Mariah Carey album)|Rainbow]]'' for the remix of [[Heartbreaker (Mariah Carey song)|Heartbreaker]] which featured [[Missy Elliott]] and [[Da Brat]].\n\nThe writers of ''Enculturation'', Steven Best and Douglas Kellner, have noted that Snoop Doggy Dogg and other rappers only condemn violence when it is directed against them, otherwise \"they celebrate it, internalize it, and embrace it as an ethos and means of self expression,\" which some believe has an effect on the black-on-black crime.<ref name=Rap-BlackRage/> The release of music videos from ''Doggystyle'' and ''The Chronic'' has enabled the artists to add visual illustrations to their lyrics, which generally involve Dr. Dre and Snoop Doggy Dogg driving around [[South Central, Los Angeles]] in a [[lowrider]] (a vehicle with lowered suspension). This imagery of the \"gangsta lifestyle\" is thought to have influenced young black males into trying to live the same lifestyle and it is also noted by T. Denean, writer of ''Pimps Up, Ho's Down: Hip Hop's Hold on Young Black Women'', that the videos highlight the representation of class, race and Black masculinity within contemporary urban America.<ref name=AmIBlackEnoughp80>Todd Boyd. (1997). ''Am I Black Enough for You?: Popular Culture from the 'hood and Beyond''. pp. 80\u201381. Indiana University Press. {{ISBN|0-253-21105-0}}.</ref>\n\n=== Subsequent work ===\n''Doggystyle'' is generally considered Snoop Doggy Dogg's best record, in addition to being his highest charting and best-selling album as his later albums were certified double Platinum, Platinum or Gold although [[Da Game Is to Be Sold, Not to Be Told]] was certified double Platinum making it his second best selling album and also his only other one to be certified multi Platinum.<ref name=AMG-Bio/><ref name=\"US200\"/><ref name=\"USR&BAl\"/><ref name=NYT-Snoop>Jon Pareles (November 26, 1996). [http://www.complex.com/music/2013/05/the-50-best-selling-rap-albums/snoop-dogg-doggystyle=nyt Machismo In Rap Atop The Charts]{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''The New York Times''. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref> It differs from following albums as his later work featured production from multiple individuals, such as [[The Neptunes]], [[Timbaland]] and [[Daz Dillinger]], with reduced input from Dr. Dre, which shows a shift from G-funk production.<ref name=AMG-Bio/> Snoop Doggy Dogg's follow-up album, ''Tha Doggfather'' (1996), did not involve Dr. Dre, as he left Death Row Records. As a result, [[DJ Pooh]] was the main beat-maker for the album. ''Tha Doggfather'' followed the methods of a G-funk record and initially sold well, but received mixed reviews and failed to produce a major hit single.<ref name=AMG-Bio/> In 1998, Snoop Dogg left Death Row and joined [[No Limit Records]], changing his stage name from Snoop Doggy Dogg to Snoop Dogg. During his tenure at the label, he continued several of the themes from ''Doggystyle'' with follow-ups to earlier songs, such as \"Gin & Juice II\" (1998) and \"[[Snoop Dogg (What's My Name Pt. 2)|Snoop Dogg (What's My Name II)]]\" (2000).<ref name=AMG-R&G/>\n\nSubsequent studio albums such as ''[[Paid tha Cost to Be da Boss]]'' (2002) and ''[[R&G (Rhythm & Gangsta): The Masterpiece]]'' (2004) exhibited a more mainstream, pop-oriented theme with new sounds, but remained \"hardcore throughout\" and featured \"plenty of street and commercial appeal\".<ref name=AMG-R&G>David Jeffries. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r719692|pure_url=yes}} R&G (Rhythm & Gangsta): The Masterpiece > Overview]. Allmusic. Accessed May 11, 2008.</ref> These releases included three hit singles, \"[[Beautiful (Snoop Dogg song)|Beautiful]]\", \"[[Drop It Like It's Hot]]\" and \"[[Signs (Snoop Dogg song)|Signs]]\". Snoop Dogg was credited for returning to his G-funk roots in 2006, which was established with his eighth studio album, ''[[Tha Blue Carpet Treatment]]'' (2006).<ref name=AMG-Bio/> The album was noted for being a \"hard and very G-Funk record\".<ref name=AMG-Bio/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=AMG/>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Abdul-Adil|first=Jaleel|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4204510.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119064345/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4204510.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 19, 2018|title=Dogged Determination Delivers a Hit for Snoop|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=December 12, 1993|accessdate=October 19, 2016|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th concise|year=2011|isbn=0-85712-595-8}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4Score = B\u2212<ref name=EW>{{cite journal|last=Browne|first=David|authorlink=David Browne (journalist)|url=http://www.ew.com/article/1993/12/10/doggystyle|title=Doggystyle|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|location=New York|date=December 10, 1993|accessdate=April 19, 2008}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Gold|first=Jonathan|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-11-21/entertainment/ca-59113_1_point-snoop-doggy-dogg|title=Snoop Doggy Dogg: A 'Style' All His Own|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 21, 1993|accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Doyle\"/>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=RollingStone>{{cite journal|author=Tour\u00e9|authorlink=Tour\u00e9 (journalist)|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/87309/review/6067798/doggystyle|title=Doggystyle: Snoop Dogg|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=January 24, 1994|accessdate=April 19, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514053855/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/87309/review/6067798/doggystyle|archivedate=May 14, 2008}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Snoop Dogg|last=Relic|first=Peter|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|edition=4th|year=2004|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|isbn=0-7432-0169-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/755 755\u201356]}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]''\n| rev9Score = 4/5<ref name=TheSource>{{cite journal|last=Dennis|first=Reginald C.|url=http://ifihavent.wordpress.com/2007/04/10/classic-review-doggystyle-in-the-source-1994/|title=Snoop Doggy Dogg: Doggystyle|work=[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]|location=New York|issue=53|date=February 1994|issn=1063-2085|accessdate=May 16, 2008}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]]''\n| rev10Score = 6/10<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]]|editor1-last=Weisbard|editor1-first=Eric|editor2-last=Marks|editor2-first=Craig|publisher=[[Vintage Books]]|year=1995|isbn=0-679-75574-8}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Doggystyle'' was released to widespread critical acclaim. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' writer [[Tour\u00e9 (journalist)|Tour\u00e9]] mentioned \"''Doggystyle'' is filled with verbal and vocal feats that meet its high expectations. It speeds through 55&nbsp;minutes of constant talk as if on a suicide hot line\".<ref name=RollingStone/> [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' noted \"It is the most limber, low-rider gangsta album to date\" and went on to say \"''Doggystyle'' is a grim, bleak-faced record. It's set in a dead-end, no-tomorrow world of cheap thrills\".<ref name=EW/> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] stated \"''Doggystyle'' and ''[[The Chronic]]'' stand proudly together as the twin pinnacles of [[West Coast hip hop|West Coast G-funk hip-hop]] of the early '90s\"<ref name=AMG/> ''Stylus'' magazine presented \"The Chronic vs. Doggystyle\" article, and stated a strong point of ''Doggystyle'' compared to Dre's album was its follow-up singles and that \"some of the album tracks are more famous than the singles\".<ref name=Stylus-TheChronicVsDoggystyle>{{cite web|last=Cohen|first=Ian|url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/vs/the-chronic-vs-doggystyle.htm|title=The Chronic vs. Doggystyle|work=[[Stylus Magazine]]|date=December 14, 2006|accessdate=May 20, 2008}}</ref> ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' magazine expressed that \"Snoop is no ordinary gangsta; that's impossible for an artist this playful. On his debut, with Dre riding shotgun anthems abound as often as gin-soaked debauchery\".<ref name=Vibe>[http://www.vibe.com/music/revolutions/2007/02/vibe_150_revs_east/ Vibe 150: West Coast] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081003055806/http://www.vibe.com/music/revolutions/2007/02/vibe_150_revs_east/ |date=October 3, 2008 }}. ''Vibe''. Accessed May 20, 2008.</ref> ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]'' magazine gave the album a 4/5 mic rating. It said Snoop Doggy Dogg emerged as a rapper who lived up to all the advance hype which came from his work on ''The Chronic'', and discussed songs on the record, stating \"If 'Murder Was The Case' is a stroke of near genius, then 'Lodi Dodi' is an example of total genius.\"<ref name=TheSource/> ''NME'' magazine called the lead single \"a pinnacle he conquered effortlessly\" and went on to name the record a \"benchmark album\".<ref name=NME-DGITBS>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/snoop-dogg/80|title=Da Game Is To Be Sold, Not To Be Told|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=May 20, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe album also received some negative criticism. Erlewine of AllMusic mentioned the album did not \"surprise or offer anything that wasn't already on ''The Chronic''\".<ref name=AMG/> Christopher John Farley noted Snoop Doggy Dogg had little examination over his emotions and feelings.<ref name=Time/> David Browne spoke of \"Ain't No Fun\", stating it was an example of how \"musically artful, yet lyrically repellent, this album can be\" and went on to say \"It's easy to be impressed one moment and appalled the next\".<ref name=EW/> Renowned rock critic [[Robert Christgau]] gave the album a \"dud\" rating,<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv294-94.php|title=Consumer Guide|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=March 1, 1994|accessdate=May 20, 2008}}</ref> which signifies \"a bad record whose details rarely merit further thought. At the upper level it may merely be overrated, disappointing, or dull. Down below it may be contemptible.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/bk-cg90/grades-90s.php|title=Key to Icons|publisher=RobertChristgau.com|accessdate=May 30, 2008}}</ref> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'''s [[Danny Kelly (journalist)|Danny Kelly]] observed: \"Snoop Doggy Dogg's record is more or less a 19-track homage to/gleeful rip off of [[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]]'s '[[Atomic Dog]]'&nbsp;... It's inclined to become a touch unimaginative; a tad, let's be honest, dull&nbsp;... And the sleeve competes with [[The Waterboys]]' ''[[Dream Harder]]'' and [[Billy Joel]]'s ''[[River of Dreams]]'' as the worst attached to a recent release.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|last=Kelly|first=Danny|authorlink=Danny Kelly (journalist)|title=Snoop Doggy Dogg: Doggystyle|work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|issue=89|date=February 1994|page=95}}</ref>\n\nDespite the initial mixed criticism, critical perception of the album later improved, as ''Doggystyle'' has earned several accolades and rankings on critics' \"best album\" lists.<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/> A review of the album's reissue upped ''Q'''s rating from three to four stars out of five. \"A modern classic,\" observed reviewer Tom Doyle.<ref name=\"Doyle\">{{cite journal|last=Doyle|first=Tom|title=Snoop Doggy Dogg: Doggystyle|work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|issue=127|date=April 1997}}</ref> ''The Source'' magazine later gave the album a classic five-mic rating.<ref name=\"Source 2002\">{{cite journal |url=http://rateyourmusic.com/list/scottbdoug/the_source_magazines_5_mic_rap_albums |title=5 Mic Albums |magazine=[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]] |year=2002 |location=New York |issn=1063-2085 |accessdate={{date|May 20, 2008|mdy}}}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\nThe information regarding accolades attributed to ''Doggystyle'' is adapted from AcclaimedMusic.net.<ref name=AcclaimedMusic>\"[http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/061024/A896.htm Snoop Doggy Dogg - ''Doggystyle'']\". AcclaimedMusic.net. Accessed May 20, 2008.</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n|-\n| [[About.com]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|United States\n| 10 Essential Hip-Hop Albums<ref name=\"About\"/>\n| 2006\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n| ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|U.S.\n| 500 CDs You Must Own Before You Die<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>\n| 2003\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n| ''Ego Trip''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|U.S.\n| Hip Hop's 25 Greatest Albums by Year 1980\u201398<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>\n| 1999\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n| Pause & Play\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|U.S.\n| Albums Inducted into a Time Capsule, One Album per Week<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n| Pause & Play\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|U.S.\n| The 90s Top 100 Essential Albums<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>\n| 1999\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n| ''Rolling Stone''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|U.S.\n| The Essential Recordings of the 90s<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>\n| 1999\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n| ''Rolling Stone'' ([[Chris Rock]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|U.S.\n| Top 25 Hip Hop Albums Ever<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>\n| 2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n| ''[[Stylus Magazine|Stylus]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|U.S.\n| Top 200 Albums of All time<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>\n| 2004\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|115\n|-\n| The Source\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|U.S.\n| The 100 Best Rap Albums<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>\n| 1998\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n| The New Nation\n| United Kingdom\n| Top 100 Albums by Black Artists<ref name=AcclaimedMusic/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30\n|-\n| Robert Dimery\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|-\n| ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=23 March 2010|publisher=Universe|isbn=978-0-7893-2074-2}}</ref>\n| 2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:10pt;\"|* denotes an unranked list\n|}\n\n== Commercial performance ==\n''Doggystyle'' debuted at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], powered by spectacular first week sales of 806,000 copies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-12-02/entertainment/ca-63303_1_debut-album|title=Snoop Doggy Dogg Leads the Pack : Rapper's Album Sets Sales Record for a Debut as Potentially Lucrative Holiday Season Begins|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 2, 1993|accessdate=August 11, 2015}}</ref> As of November 2015, the album had sold seven million copies in the United States, and over eleven million copies worldwide.<ref name=Sales/> It was certified four times [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] on May 31, 1994.<ref name=RIAA/> It is Snoop Doggy Dogg's most successful album; his following albums were certified single or double platinum.<ref name=RIAA-SnoopDogg>[https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Snoop%20Dogg&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2007&sort=Artist&perPage=25 RIAA Searchable database - Snoop Dogg] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017084407/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Snoop%20Dogg&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2007&sort=Artist&perPage=25 |date=October 17, 2015 }}. Recording Industry Association of America. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref> ''Doggystyle'' first appeared on music charts in 1993, peaking on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] at No. 1.<ref name=\"US200\"/><ref name=\"USR&BAl\"/> It re-peaked at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200 in January 1994, when it was already certified three times platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=Variety>Bruce Haring (February 2, 1994). [http://www.variety.com/article/VR117970.html?categoryid=16&cs=1 Albums chart course to blockbuster sales]. Variety. Retrieved June 5, 2008.</ref> The record was mildly successful in Europe, reaching No. 18 in Sweden, No. 21 in Germany and No. 35 in Austria. It also peaked at No. 25 on the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] album chart.<ref name=\"AUT\"/><ref name=\"GER\"/><ref name=\"NZ\"/><ref name=\"SWE\"/> At the end of 1994, the album was No. 3 on the ''Billboard'' Year-End Top Albums Chart and No. 1 on the ''Billboard'' Year-End Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums Chart.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/1994/the-billboard-200 The Billboard 200 1994]. ''Billboard''. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=Top+R%26B%2FHip-Hop+Albums&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1994 Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums 1994] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071211065742/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=Top+R%26B%2FHip-Hop+Albums&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1994 |date=2007-12-11 }}. ''Billboard''. Retrieved April 16, 2008.</ref> It re-entered the charts in 2003, peaking on the Ireland Albums Top&nbsp;75 at No. 70.<ref name=\"IRL\"/> {{As of|September 2015}}, it had spent a total of 74 nonconsecutive weeks on the ''Billboard'' 200 album chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2015-09-19|title=Top 200 Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2015-09-19|accessdate=April 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n* All songs produced by [[Dr. Dre]].\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 55:05\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title1   = Bathtub\n| note     = featuring [[The Lady of Rage and Nanci Fletcher]]\n| writer1  = [[Snoop Dogg|Calvin Broadus, Jr.]]\n| length1  = 1:50\n| title2   = G Funk Intro\n| note2    = featuring [[George Clinton (funk musician)|George Clinton]], Dr. Dre and [[The Lady of Rage]]\n| writer2  = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Robin Allen}}\n| length2  = 2:24\n| title3   = [[Gin and Juice]]\n| note3    = featuring [[Daz Dillinger]] and David Ruffin' Jr.\n| writer3  = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|[[Dr. Dre|Andre Young]]|[[Harry Wayne Casey]]|[[Richard Finch (musician)|Richard Finch]]}}\n| length3  = 3:31\n| title4   = W Balls\n| note4    = featuring Nanci Fletcher, Malia Franklin and [[Ricky Harris]]\n| writer4  = Broadus, Jr.\n| length4  = 0:36\n| title5   = Tha Shiznit\n| note5    = \n| writer5  = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Young}}\n| length5  = 4:04\n| title6   = Domino Intro\n| writer6  = Broadus, Jr.\n| length6  = 0:37\n| title7   = [[La Di Da Di#Cover versions|Lodi Dodi]]\n| note7    = featuring Nanci Fletcher \n| writer7  = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|[[Doug E. Fresh|Douglas Davis]]|[[Hachidai Nakamura]]|[[Rokusuke Ei|Ei Rokusuke]]|[[Slick Rick|Ricky Walters]]}}\n| length7  = 4:24\n| title8   = [[Murder Was the Case (song)|Murder Was the Case]]\n| note8    = featuring Daz Dillinger\n| writer8  = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Young|Delmar Arnaud}}\n| length8  = 3:38\n| title9   = Serial Killa\n| note9    = featuring [[The D.O.C.|D.O.C.]], [[RBX]] and [[Tha Dogg Pound]]\n| writer9  = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Young|Arnaud|[[Bootsy Collins]]}}\n| length9  = 3:32\n| title10  = [[What's My Name? (Snoop Doggy Dogg song)|Who Am I? (What's My Name?)]]\n| note10   = featuring Jewell, Dr. Dre and Tony Green\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Young|[[George Clinton (musician)|George Clinton]]|[[Garry Shider]]|David Spradley}}\n| length10 = 4:06\n| title11  = For All My Niggaz & Bitches\n| note11   = featuring [[Tha Dogg Pound]] and [[The Lady of Rage]]\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Arnaud|Ricardo Brown|Allen}}\n| length11 = 4:43\n| title12  = Ain't No Fun (If the Homies Can't Have None)\n| note12   = featuring [[Nate Dogg]], [[Warren G]], Nanci Fletcher and [[Kurupt]]\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Young|Brown|Nathaniel Hale|Warren Griffin}}\n| length12 = 4:06\n| title13  = Chronic Relief Intro\n| writer13 = Broadus, Jr.\n| length13 = 0:33\n| title14  = [[Doggy Dogg World]]\n| note14   = featuring Tha Dogg Pound and [[The Dramatics]]\n| writer14 = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Arnaud|Brown|[[Richard \"Dimples\" Fields]]|[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|James Harris III]]|[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Terry Lewis]]}}\n| length14 = 5:05\n| title15  = Class Room Intro (performed by [[Bow Wow (rapper)|Shad Moss]])\n| writer15 = Broadus, Jr.\n| length15 = 0:44\n| title16  = Gz and Hustlas\n| note16   = featuring Nanci Fletcher\n| writer16 = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Arnaud|[[Don Blackman]]}}\n| length16 = 3:51\n| title17  = Checkin'\n| writer17 = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Young}}\n| length17 = 0:57\n| title18  = Gz Up, Hoes Down\n| note18   = featuring Hug\n| writer18 = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Young|Arnaud}}\n| length18 = 2:21\n| title19  = Pump Pump\n| note19   = featuring [[Illegal (group)|Lil Malik]]\n| writer19 = {{hlist|Broadus, Jr.|Young|Jamal Phillips|Malik Edwards}}\n| length19 = 3:42\n}}\n\n===Notes===\n* \"Gz Up, Hoes Down\" was omitted on all but the original pressings, due to sample and clearance issues. On the original release's back cover, it is erroneously listed after \"Pump Pump\" instead of immediately before.\n* The original pressings of the album which contain \"Gz Up, Hoes Down\" list \"W Balls\" separately on the album's artwork. They also include a listing for \"Tha Next Episode\". This song did not exist on any copy of the album. It leaked however, in the late 2000s.\n* Later pressings of the album, which remove \"Gz Up, Hoes Down\", do not list either of these tracks on the album's artwork, although \"W Balls\" is featured.\n* [[Murder Was the Case]] was later turned into a film.\n\n===Cut tracks===\n* \"Gz Up, Hoes Down\" (featuring Hug) - omitted on all but the original pressings, due to sample and clearance issues. \n* \"Tha Next Episode\" (featuring [[Dr. Dre]]) - listed on the track listing provided to retailers before the album's release, but does not feature on any pressings of the album. The instrumental was later used for [[Warren G]]'s track \"Runnin' Wit No Breaks\" from his album, ''[[Regulate...G Funk Era]]''<ref name=\"djluicidal.com\">http://www.djluicidal.com/2009/10/the-death-row-vaults/{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The pair later recorded a track entitled \"[[The Next Episode]]\" for Dre's second studio album, ''[[2001 (Dr. Dre album)|2001]]'', which is completely different from the original.\n* \"Doggystyle\" (featuring [[Jewell (singer)|Jewell]] & [[George Clinton (funk musician)|George Clinton]]) - recorded during the album sessions, remaining unreleased until its inclusion on the compilation album ''[[Death Row: The Lost Sessions Vol. 1]]''<ref name=\"djluicidal.com\"/>\n* \"The Root of All Evil (Outro)\" (featuring [[Teena Marie]]) - recorded during the album sessions, remaining unreleased until its inclusion on the compilation album ''Death Row: The Lost Sessions Vol. 1''. The instrumental was later used for the remix of \"[[California Love]]\", by [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]] featuring [[Dr. Dre]].\n* \"Every Single Day\" (featuring [[Kurupt]], [[Jewell (singer)|Jewell]] and [[Nate Dogg]]) - recorded during the album sessions, remaining unreleased until an alternate version was released on ''[[Tha Dogg Pound]]'' compilation album ''[[2002 (Tha Dogg Pound album)|2002]]''.\n\n== Personnel ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* [[Snoop Doggy Dogg]] \u2013  [[lead vocals]]\n* [[Dr. Dre]] \u2013 producer, vocals\n* [[Daz Dillinger]] \u2013 vocals, performer\n* [[Sam Sneed]] - performer, inspiration\n* [[Ulrich Wild]] \u2013 engineer\n* [[Tha Dogg Pound]] \u2013 performer\n* [[Warren G]] \u2013 performer\n* [[The D.O.C.]] \u2013 performer\n* [[The Lady of Rage]] \u2013 performer\n* [[RBX]] \u2013 performer\n* [[Kurupt]] \u2013 performer\n* [[Nate Dogg]] \u2013 performer\n{{col-2}}\n* [[The Dramatics]] \u2013 performer\n* Emanuel Dean \u2013 producer\n* [[Chris \"The Glove\" Taylor]] \u2013 songwriter, mixing\n* [[Suge Knight]] \u2013 executive producer\n* [[Bernie Grundman]] \u2013 mastering\n* Chi Modu \u2013 photography\n* Nanci Fletcher \u2013 performer, vocals (featured and background)\n* [[Dan Winters]] \u2013 photography\n* Kimberly Holt \u2013 artwork\n* Kimberly Brown \u2013 project coordinator\n* Joe Cool \u2013 cover artwork\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Chart (1993\u20132015)\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{albumchart|Australia|24|artist=Snoop Doggy Dogg|album=Doggystyle|accessdate=May 29, 2014|refname=\"AUS\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" {{albumchart|Austria|35|artist=Snoop Doggy Dogg|album=Doggystyle|accessdate=May 29, 2014|refname=\"AUT\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Canadian Albums ([[RPM (magazine)